How exactly is the server set up

(Figure from https://www.marquette.edu/high-performance-computing/architecture.php)

How exactly is the server set up

This node (highlighted in red) is the shared computing resoures you all are using when you log into Bayes.

  • It doesnt have a lot of computing power. You dont have as much RAM compared to the compute node, and also you cant parallelize your code much anyways
  • Its also a shared resources, so even if youre crazy and run a big job on the login node, its at the detriment of everyone else who is simply trying to log into Bayes
  • In conclusion, you should not use the login node for heavy jobs (i.e., loading in big data files, or performing calculations that take more a couple minutes to finish)
  • The login node is ideal for:
    • Simple things for navigating and moving files/folders
    • Opening R to do quick calculations/plots (nothing too complicated these should be things you would happy to do on your local laptop, but its just easier to do them on the server)

More on server etiquette

Well talk about 2 most basic forms of etiquette

One: Checking the traffic on different partitions to know which partition to submit your job to.

  • You can check the status of all the jobs on the server via squeue (instead of squeue --me)

  • (The usernames crossed out for anonymitiy, but remember, because the server is a public resource, everyone can see everyone elses job being run.)
  • The most common type of server drama Ive seen if other departments is that one student hogs up all the nodes for multiple days in a row, and trust me, it gets really dramatic really fast. Dont let yourself be the source of the drama.
    • If youre parallelizing code, be mindful of how aggressively you parallelize it.
    • Realistically, a job that takes a couple hours to finish is alright. Submit your job, go get food, go on a break, or go to sleep, and then check your job status when youre back.
    • This is why its incredibly important to test your code before you start your massive job. You dont want to spend a couple hours to run your code, only for it to crash.
  • You can also check the status of all the partitions you have access to via sinfo.

  • A note about wording. Each node has many cores inside it. Your job takes up a complete core (which cannot be shared), but your job might be on the same node as another persons job.
  • Your screenshot will likely information about the student partition (which I, Kevin, do not have access to, and hence not shown when I run sinfo)

Two: Setting the amount of memory and time your job takes appropriately.

Recall these lines in demo_bayes.slurm:

#SBATCH --time=12:00:00
#SBATCH --mem-per-cpu=10gb
  • The first line (--time) is (in hours:minutes:seconds) the maximum time your job is allotted. Typically, theres no harm in keeping this 12 hours even if your job takes much less time
  • The second line (--mem-per-cpu) is the real bottleneck. Requesting more memory doet not make your job finish faster. All this does is ensure your large datasets and results can fit in the R workspace.
    • More on how to determine what is a reasonable amount of space to allocate next week

Onto making a simulation

Hmm why are we even doing simulations?

  • As youve experienced in all your other classes, for every problem, there are tons and tons of computational/statistical methods that researchers have developed over the decades
    • Everyone claims their method is the best (more on this in the last class)
    • You, however, should be a healthy skeptic even if everyone were truthful, how do you know which method works the best for the specific problems you are trying to solve?

Was is the ideal scenario for a simulation?

  • You have some computational/statistical methods that you want to compare against
  • Obviously, to make this a fair and meaningful comparison, you need to know:
      1. The ground truth
      1. A way to generate randomness (so you can assess if one method is doing better across many datasets, or just simply one dataset)
  • Additionally, itll be nice if you have a knob to make your simulations easier or harder
    • You would hope all the methods youre comparing against are reasonable, meaning they should all ace the easy setting.
    • However, you would hope as you make the problem harder and harder, certain methods rise to the occasion, and others start struggle (and this would make it clear to you which specific method you like)
  • All these goals can be achieved in a simulation study

What is a simulation study?

  • A controlled way to measure how good different methods are
  • This very simple statement is liced with a lot of assumptions to make it tangible:
    • Of course, you need to define what good means
    • To measure what good means, you probably need to know 1) what the correct answer is, and 2) how your method guess/estimates what an appropriate answer is based on data
    • To know how to define the correct answer despite the method seeing on noisy data, you need to also define a way to generate the data
  • So theres a lot of moving components. At mimimum theres
    • A data generation mechanism
    • A few to many different methods (that take in data as input, and output results in a comparable format)
    • A way to measure how good/bad a method is

The parts of simulation plan

  • First: What are you trying to study
  • Then: Define the different levels of your simulation. This is how you are changing the problem across the simulation. (This is the knob that controls how easy/hard the simulation is)
    • Have more and more variables? (About the data)
    • Have more and more samples? (About the data)
    • Have more and more noise? (About the data)
    • Have more and more complex relations between the variables? (About the data)
    • Have a grid of parameters for the methods? (About the method)
  • Then: Define (based on your data generation mechanism) what you are trying to measure or what youre trying to estimate. Make this as concrete as possible
  • Then: Write down all the methods you are going to compare against
  • Then: For each method, write down how you measure how good/bad each method is. This is an error metric that typically is based on the methods outputs (and possibly, the datas correct answer)
    • Note: Sometimes its hard to even know what the correct answer is. (Think of our partial cliques its very easy to construct a graph with a partial clique, but sometimes, its not that easy to really know what is the largest partial clique)
  • Then: write down how many trials you want in each level
    • The (Number of levels) x (Number of methods) x (Number of trials) is a simple way to determine how problem-instances our simulation has
  • Finally: Think about the output of all these numbers. How are you going to manage these numbers? How will you plot the results?

To check how much memory your job required

Say your job ID is 409633.Rout. To look at the memory usage of this job, run: sacct -j 409633 --format=JobID,JobName,MaxRSS,MaxRSSNode%15.

This yields the following output:

This job required 143496 Kilobytes (about 0.14 Gigabytes) to finish.

This number tells you how to appropriate adjust your memory usage in your SLURM script the next time you run it.

Lets take a look at the demo simulation Ive given you

rm(list=ls())
set.seed(10)
library(UWBiost561)

imp_numbers <- 1:15
trials <- 5
alpha_vec <- c(0.5, 0.95)

# loop over the levels
level_trial_list <- lapply(alpha_vec, function(alpha){
  print(paste("Value of alpha:", alpha))
  
  # loop over the different trials for this level
  trial_list <- lapply(1:trials, function(trial){
    print(paste("Working on trial:", trial))
    # to freeze the randomness of adj_mat
    set.seed(trial) 
    
    # generate the data
    data <- generate_partial_clique(n = 10)
    adj_mat <- data$adj_mat
    
    # loop over the methods for this trial
    result_list <- lapply(imp_numbers, function(imp_number){
      
      # to freeze the randomness of the method
      set.seed(trial) 
      cat('*')
      result <- compute_maximal_partial_clique_master(
        adj_mat = adj_mat,
        alpha = alpha,
        number = imp_number,
        time_limit = 30
      )
      
      return(result)
    })
    names(result_list) <- paste("Implementation:", imp_numbers)
    cat("\n")
    
    return(result_list)
  })
  names(trial_list) <- paste("Trial:", 1:trials)
  print("====")
  
  return(trial_list)
})

names(level_trial_list) <- paste0("alpha:", alpha_vec)

# it's always useful to save the date and R session info
date_of_run <- Sys.time()
session_info <- devtools::session_info()

save(level_trial_list, # save your results
     alpha_vec,  # save which alphas you used 
     date_of_run, session_info,
     file = "~/demo_simulation.RData")

  • This maximizes the chances your results are easily reproducible

  • This is where you declare:
  • How many trials do you want per level (Here, keeping it simple, a fixed number of 5 per level)
  • What are the levels? That is, what do you want to vary across the simulation study in terms of what youre evaluating?
  • The levels are sometimes about the data generating mechanism (i.e., more nodes in your graph). Here, its about the method arguments were changing the required density of the partial clique, alpha

  • Next, we want to loop over the trials
  • This is yet another lapply(). This is the middle list.
  • Usually, in a simulation study, the trials refer to different instances of generating random data for the same parameter setting
  • Loosely speaking, each dataset in the the same trial should be of equal difficulty, but in a literal sense, are all slightly different (because the data generation mechanism is random)

  • Here is where we run all 15 different methods
  • Remeber that imp_numbers is 1 through 15, and were using number=imp_number inside the lapply().
  • Hence, result_list is a list of results. It will have length 15, where each element of the list is the result of one of the 15 implementation of compute_maximal_partial_clique
  • Sidenote: Its very useful to have one master function that deploys all the different implementations. This makes your simulation much easier to read
    • In this homework, I made compute_maximal_partial_clique_master() for you, but when you write your own simulation study beyond this course, you might want to do something similar
    • This compute_maximal_partial_clique_master() also helps to ensure that all the methods provide an output in the same format
    • Remember, the result of any compute_maximal_partial_clique implementation is a list itself!

})

# it's always useful to save the date and R session info
date_of_run <- Sys.time()
session_info <- devtools::session_info()

save(level_trial_list, # save your results
     alpha_vec,  # save which alphas you used 
     date_of_run, session_info,
     file = "~/demo_simulation.RData")
  • Its useful to set the seed again right before each method, since you dont know if certain methods use any randomness or not
rm(list=ls())
set.seed(10)
library(UWBiost561)

imp_numbers <- 1:15
trials <- 5
alpha_vec <- c(0.5, 0.95)

# loop over the levels
level_trial_list <- lapply(alpha_vec, function(alpha){
  print(paste("Value of alpha:", alpha))
  
  # loop over the different trials for this level
  trial_list <- lapply(1:trials, function(trial){
    print(paste("Working on trial:", trial))
    # to freeze the randomness of adj_mat
    set.seed(trial) 
    
    # generate the data
    data <- generate_partial_clique(n = 10)
    adj_mat <- data$adj_mat
    
    # loop over the methods for this trial
    result_list <- lapply(imp_numbers, function(imp_number){
      
      # to freeze the randomness of the method
      set.seed(trial) 
      cat('*')
      result <- compute_maximal_partial_clique_master(
        adj_mat = adj_mat,
        alpha = alpha,
        number = imp_number,
        time_limit = 30
      )
      
      return(result)
    })
    names(result_list) <- paste("Implementation:", imp_numbers)
    cat("\n")
    
    return(result_list)
  })
  names(trial_list) <- paste("Trial:", 1:trials)
  print("====")
  
  return(trial_list)
})

  • Now save your results!
  • I find it useful to save the current time and the R session info (just in case I need to double check which version of certain packages were used)
  • The two important things you want to save are: your simulation results (here, level_trial_list) and what the values of the different levels were (here, alpha_vec)
  • (You would load these results in, just like any other R data object, and then analyze all your results, make plots, etc.)

How to think about a (generic) simulation output

Heres how to think about the simulation output

  • The simulation results are essentially 3 nested lists

    • The top layer (blue, level_trial_list) is the list that contains all the simulation results
    • Each element of the blue list is the simulation results for a different level (for example, a different sample size).
    • Each element of the blue list a list itself: The middle layer (orange, trial_list) is a list that contains: For this level, what are all the results across all the different trials
    • Each element of the orange list is the simulation results for a specific level across all the trials
    • Each element of the orange list is a list itself: The last layer (purple, result_list) is a list that contains: For a specific level and a specific trial, how did each of my methods perform?
    • Each element of the purple list is a list itself: Its the outputs of a particular method

  • If youre not familiar with handling so much data, dont worry. This takes a long time to digest.

  • You do not need to abide by this. Everyone has their personal preference on how to organize simulation outputs. What Im teaching is simply my personal recommendation since I think its a good balance between complexity and usefulness
